                        <div class="container-fluid" id="div_4">
                            <div class="row">
                                <div class="col-lg-12">
                                    <h1 class="section-heading">Research</h1>
                                    <p class="lead section-lead">Are people ready to be monitored in their own house? That is the first question we have studied while creating our system. We realised that most of the possible consumers we have interrogated are very pessimistic when it comes to installing sensors in their own house. They are scared of feeling observed, being reliable on electronics to help them realise daily tasks, and finally do not want to have a visible object that ruins the layout of a room. Therefore we had to find a way of getting the information we want without making the user uncomfortable. Here are the solutions we came up with:
<br>
The devices on the door cannot be installed on top of it. They have to be present on the side of it. Having a given sensor that points down towards their head makes the user very uncomfortable whereas having it at hand level, makes it easy to reach and moreover makes people at ease.
<br>
People want to know what the is the current state the system is in: if its turned on/off, if its connecting and if it is actually detecting someone. Furthermore they also want to have the possibility to have a certain control on each device (being able to detach it, turn it off).
<br>
The type of sensor used by the system also has an impact on how consumers fell about the product. For instance they do not feel very at ease if a camera constantly records them but are ok if a heat sensor just measures where they are.</p>
                                    <p class="section-paragraph"></p>
                                </div>
